# From scanned PDFs to ERP-ready data

Distribution businesses receive orders in countless formats — handwritten fax sheets, scanned PDFs, email attachments, and even photos taken on a warehouse floor. Each one needs to become a structured line item in an ERP system before fulfillment can begin.

Traditionally, this means a data entry clerk opens each document, deciphers the content, and manually keys in product codes, quantities, and delivery dates. The process is slow, error-prone, and difficult to scale.

## How AI changes the equation

Modern AI order processing works in three stages:

1. **Document ingestion** — The system accepts any input format: PDF, image, email body, or WhatsApp message. OCR and layout analysis extract raw text while preserving table structures.

2. **Intelligent parsing** — Large language models interpret the extracted text in context. They resolve ambiguous product references, normalize units of measure, and flag potential issues like unusually large quantities.

3. **ERP-ready output** — The parsed data maps to the customer's specific product catalog, producing structured records ready for direct import into SAP, Microsoft Dynamics, or any ERP system with an API.

## The accuracy question

The natural concern is accuracy. In practice, AI order processing consistently achieves 95%+ accuracy on clearly printed documents and 85-90% on challenging handwritten orders. The key is that the system flags low-confidence items for human review rather than guessing silently.

This means the human role shifts from data entry to exception handling — reviewing only the items the AI is uncertain about.

## Real-world impact

For a mid-sized distributor processing 200 orders per day, AI order processing typically reduces manual handling time by 60-70%. More importantly, it eliminates the class of errors that come from fatigue and repetition — transposed digits, wrong product codes, missed line items.

The result is faster order-to-fulfillment cycles, fewer returns due to picking errors, and a data entry team that can focus on customer relationships instead of keystroke work.
